  <Fragment slot="lead">
    <p class="lead">The best AeroPress Go recipe is the one you can actually repeat half asleep in a hotel room, at your desk, or on a campsite table that wobbles every time you touch it. For most people, that means a simple 15-gram brew with medium-fine grounds, hot but not boiling water, and a slow press that lands somewhere between clean pour over and a tiny French press in a really good mood.</p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="quick-answer">
    <h2 id="quick-answer">Quick answer</h2>
    <p><strong>Start here:</strong> use <strong>15g coffee</strong>, <strong>240g water</strong>, a <strong>medium-fine grind</strong>, and water around <strong>185 to 195°F</strong> or <strong>85 to 91°C</strong>. Add a small first pour, give it a quick swirl, top it up, steep for about <strong>90 seconds total</strong>, then press slowly. That is the easiest AeroPress Go recipe to get right day after day.</p>
    <p>If you want the short version, think of it like this: not espresso-concentrated, not diner-coffee thin, just right in the middle. Sweet enough to taste the beans, full enough to feel satisfying, and forgiving enough that one sloppy morning does not ruin the cup.</p>

